AGI - A thousand arbitrators to elect the president of AIA. As the AGI learns, this is the proposal that will arrive today at the National Committee of the Association by the Committee for the revision of the elective regulation chaired by the vice-president of AIA, Alberto Zaroli, which includes the councilmen of the national committee Antonio Zappi and Riccardo Camiciottoli, the representatives of the presidents of the 20 Italian regions and the autonomous provinces of Trento and Bolzano and the lawyer Valerio Di Stasio, responsible for the experts called to express themselves.
&nbsp;
Here is the possible breakthrough after the protests triggered by the initiative of the President of the Federcalcio Gabriele Gravina> who, in recent days, had proposed the election to universal suffrage of number one with the call to the urns of all the senior arbitrators to overcome the current system in which each section expresses some delegates who then indicate the president.
&nbsp;
In the Federal Council of 14 May, in the face of the malumori, Gravina had given the opportunity to present its document in line with the principles indicated by the Federation. President Carlo Pacifici had then formed a Committee for the revision of the Elective Regulation, which today will put on the table its proposal which, although not in line with the initial idea of Gravina, recognizes the need to expand the electoral base to increase the democracy of the association. &nbsp;&nbsp; The broadly shared idea emerged from the comparison and sharing of opinions among sectional presidents, who recognized the importance of reducing the most problematic aspects of voting policy > which in recent times has worn out the integrity of AIA. It provides for a qualified and proportionally representative electoral body to be established of all regions and sectional chairmen, composed of about 1000 units. This was the proposal supported by the two councilmen of the National Committee, the Venetian Antonio Zappi and the Campania Michele Affinito and on which they found a substantial almost unanimity all the regions.
&nbsp;
In the perspective of greater clarity of AIA, other corrections were proposed: the duration of the designator charge must be biennial, > to ensure greater autonomy and serenity in work with the arbitrator group; the incompatibility between the role of arbitrator in activity or member of a technical organ and that of delegate in the elections, in order to avoid conflicts of interest; the impossibility for delegates and sectional presidents to assume technical assignments and appointments in the two years after the elections, to prevent the possibility that delegates can become bearers of personal political interests. Except for surprises, the National Committee today should ratify the proposal that will then be brought to the Federal Council to which the last word will be on the methods of choice of the President of AIA.(AGI)

